The paper deals with computational approaches for graph problems, specifically the zero forcing problem and related problems. The zero forcing problem is a well-known problem in graph theory and is closely related to topics such as graph coloring, domination, and connectivity. Therefore, cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves combinatorial algorithms and integer programming models, which are common in cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-categories. The paper also discusses numerical comparisons of different algorithms, which falls under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes new algorithms for connected zero forcing and controlling propagation time, which are related to machine learning and optimization, and hence cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a possible sub-category.
